The paper describes the application of temporal data mining for analyzing fault logs in an engine assembly plant, which involves a complex and heavily automated distributed-control process. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories, as these fields are concerned with developing algorithms and techniques for automated analysis and decision-making. The paper also discusses the incorporation of domain-specific knowledge using heuristic rules, which suggests that it may be relevant to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category, which deals with the design and development of software systems. Additionally, the paper describes the use of frequent episode discovery, which is a method for discovering patterns in temporal data, indicating that it may be relevant to the Data Mining (cs.DM) sub-category. Finally, the paper focuses on the application of these techniques in the manufacturing domain, suggesting that it may also be relevant to the Computer Engineering (cs.CE) sub-category, which deals with the design and development of computer systems and hardware.
